$$ \begin{align*} \tan \delta \theta = \frac{ \delta u \cdot \delta t }{ \delta y} \approx \delta \theta && \Longrightarrow && \tau \propto \frac{ \delta \theta }{ \delta t } = \frac{ \delta u }{ \delta y } && \Longrightarrow && \tau = \mu \frac{du}{dy} \end{align*} $$

$\delta u$ (Velocity) $\text{[m/s]}$
$\delta \theta$ (Shear Strain) $\text{[rad]}$
$\tau$ (Shear Stress) $[\text{N}/\text{m}^2]$
$\mu$ (Dynamic Viscosity) $[\text{N.s}/\text{m}^2]$
$du/dy$ (Shear Rate) $[1/\text{s}]$

1.3. (Control Volume)

(Control Volume)?

(Control Volume) , (System) . , .

(Conservation of Mass)

$$ \begin{align*} \Delta m_{CV} = \Sigma m_{in} - \Sigma m_{out} && \therefore \quad \frac{dm_{CV}}{dt} = \Sigma \dot{m}_{in} - \Sigma \dot{m}_{out} = \dot{m}_{CV} \end{align*} $$

$m_{CV}$ $\text{[kg]}$
$\dot{m}_{CV}$ (Mass Rate) $\text{[kg/s]}$

(Conservation of Energy)

$$ \begin{align*} \Delta E_{CV} = \Sigma E_{in} - \Sigma E_{out} && \therefore \quad \frac{dE_{CV}}{dt} = \frac{dKE}{dt} + \frac{dPE}{dt} + \frac{dU}{dt} = \dot{E}_{CV} \end{align*} $$

$E_{CV}$ $\text{[J]}$
$\dot{E}_{CV}$ (Power) $\text{[J/s]}$
$KE$ (Kinetic Energy) $\text{[J]}$
$PE$ (Potential Energy) $\text{[J]}$
$U$ (Internal Energy) $\text{[J]}$

  • , $\text{Re}$ (Reynolds Number):

(Reynolds Number) . (Laminar Flow) (Turbulent Flow) .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{Re} = \frac{ \text{inertial force} }{ \text{viscous force} } = \frac{ \rho u L }{\mu} = \frac{ u L }{\nu} && \end{align*} $$

$\rho$ (Density) $[\text{kg}/\text{m}^3]$
$u$ (Velocity) $[text{m/s}]$
$L$ (Characteristic Length) $[\text{m}]$
$\mu$ (Dynamic Viscosity) $[\text{N.s}/\text{m}^2]$
$\nu$ (Kinematic Viscosity) $[\text{m}^2/\text{s}]$

(Control Surface) . (Pipe) (Hydraulic Diameter), $D_h$ .

. 2100 4000 . (Transient) . , $\text{Re}_{cr}$ , .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{In a pipe,} \\ \\ \text{Re} &< 2100 \quad \text{for laminar flow} \\ \\ 2100 \leq \text{Re} &\leq 4000 \quad \text{for transient flow} \\ \\ \text{Re} &> 4000 \quad \text{for turbulent flow} \\ \\ \text{On a plate,} \\ \\ \text{Re} &< \text{Re}_{cr} \approx 10^5 \quad \text{for laminar flow} \\ \\ \text{Re} &> \text{Re}_{cr} \approx 10^5 \quad \text{for turbulent flow} \end{align*} $$
  • , $\text{Ma}$ (Mach Number):

(Mach Number) .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{Ma} = \frac{ \text{flow velocity} }{ \text{speed of sound} } = \frac{u}{c} \end{align*} $$

$c$ (Speed of Sound) $[\text{m/s}]$

0.3 (Incompressible) .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{Ma} < 0.3 \quad \text{for incompressible flow} \end{align*} $$
  • , $\text{Pr}$ (Prandtl Number):

(Prandtl Number) .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{Pr} = \frac{ \text{viscous diffusion rate} }{ \text{thermal diffusion rate} } = \frac{\nu}{\alpha} = \frac{ c_p \mu }{k} \end{align*} $$

$\alpha$ (Thermal Diffusivity) $[\text{m}^2/\text{s}]$
$c_p$ (Specific Heat) $[\text{J/kg.K}]$
$k$ (Thermal Conductivity) $[\text{W/m.K}]$

.

  • , $\text{Fr}$ (Froude Number):

(Foude Number) .

$$ \begin{align*} \text{Fr} = \frac{ \text{inertial force} }{ \text{gravitational force} } = \frac{u}{ \sqrt{ gL } } \end{align*} $$

1 (Supercritical Flow), 1 (Subcritical Flow) .

  • , $\text{Nu}$ (Nusselt Number):
$$ \begin{align*} \text{Nu} = \frac{ \text{convection} }{ \text{conduction} } = \frac{ h L }{ k } \end{align*} $$

$h$ (Convection Heat Transfer Coefficient) $[\text{W}/\text{m}^2 \text{.K}]$
